defaultC
defaultontributions (NIC) where appropriate
default) has caused 
defaultsome LLPs to distribute profits to
default corporate members
default owned by 
defaultindividual 
defaultmembers rather than to 
defaultindividual 
defaultmembers themselves; and
default■
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe different NIC treatment bet
defaultween self employed individuals, including partners in a partnership,
default and employees
default 
defaultrelate
defaultd
default to 
defaultemployers
default’
default contribution
defaults of 13.8%
default has caused some LLPs to appoint individuals as members who HMRC believe should more properly be taxed as employees.
default3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe 
defaultstated 
defaultpolicy objective is to prevent th
defaulte
default avoidance described above
default and we have been advised by HMRC 
defaultt
defaulthat it is not intended to impact upon the taxation of 
defaultgenuine 
defaultequity partners.
default 
defaultWe support the policy objective.  We have also been advised that the approach taken in drafting the legislation has been to base it on case law principles with the intention of 
defaultcreating a relatively straightforward, forward looking test which can be applied year on year.  
defaultWe support this approach and believe that the three factors used in the draft legislation of profit sharing, management and capital are, on balance, those most 
defaultprominently featured in previous case law. 
default4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever,
default as currently drafted we do not believe that the legislation achieves its aim.  It is too vague and is not capable of being interpreted without the use of the supporting guidance.  The guidance itself exp
defaultands rather than merely clarifies the scope of the legislation.  This is bad law and we believe that it will result in the 
defaultlegislation hav
defaulting
default far wider scope than its st
defaultated intent
default.  In effect 
defaultit does have the capacity to impact 
defaultsignificant numbers of genu
defaultine
default equity partners
default. 
default5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default The individuals from HMRC who have been tasked with this job appear to welcome 
defaultinput and to be willing to make amendments where they will improve both the legislation and the guidance.  However, we believe that the current proposed t
defaultimetable of an effective date of 6 April 2014 means that insufficient changes will be feasible and that only solution is to defer the introduction of the legislation, ideally until Finance Bill 2015, while this further work is carried out.
defaultI set out our co
defaultncerns in more detail below.
defaultLegislationdefault6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe
default 
defaultdraft legislation is 
defaultvery broadly drafted and has few defined
default terms.  
defaultFor 
defaultexample
default 
default,a
default key phrase upon which much of the discussion lies is the phrase “substantially wholly”
default in s863B(1)(b)
default.  This is not defined in
default the legislation but is stated unequivocally in the guidance to mean 80%.  
default In addition, 
defaultduring discussions, HMRC have clarified that a factor which will determine whether condition A applies or not (
defaults863B(
default1)-(3)) is whether an individual is paid in priori
defaultty to his fellow members.  This is not mentioned in the legislation but could be included relatively easily
default.
default 
default7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe legislation includes a capital test (Condition C).  Broadly a member requires capital in excess of 25% of any disguised remuneration in order to fail the condition and avoid becoming a salaried member.  We believe that the level of capital required in 
defaultthis test discriminates unfairly against non capital-intensive businesses and those firms which manage cash flow efficiently.  There is a risk that including this test will drive firms to adopt uncommercial behaviour
default as it may encourage firms to require me
defaultmbers to inject capital, notwithstanding that this may not be needed by the business.  
default8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe
default capital
default test also only allows 
defaultformal 
defaultcapital to be included in the calculation. We disagree that only fixed capital is relevant. Large amounts of funding for workin
defaultg capital and investment come not from capital subscriptions made by partners, but from the retention of internally generated funds otherwise payable to partners, such that at any point in time the total investment by the partner group significantly exceed
defaults the formal capital which they inject. This deferral of payment is a feature which distinguishes partners from employees (employees would expect to receive the vast majority of their remuneration during the year rather than after the year-end).  For examp
defaultle, the Statement of Financial Position at page 48 of KPMG’s Annual Report for the year ended 30 September 2013 shows that while the formal capital contributed by members was £50m, the total members’ interests were £354m.  
defaultThe balance of £304m represents t
defaulthe net of unallocated or undrawn profits.  We believe that any capital test should allow all of these interests to be classed as capital.
default 
default9
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe legislation is drafted by reference to tax years.  The tax basis period for LLPs is the accounting period.  This 
defaultis also the period for which many LLPs agree member remuneration structures and capital.  We believe that the legislation will be easier to apply for both taxpayers and HMRC if it were redrafted by reference to accounting periods and therefore recommend th
defaultat this is done.
default10
default 
defaultSome firms
default,
default including KPMG
default,
default award retiring partners fixed profit shares or priority payments in their final year of membership or agree the profits of that final year at the time of retirement rather than following the end of the year when
default profits are known. 
default While in some instances it will be the case that no further services will be performed by the member following the agreement (see 
defaults862B(
default1)(a)), this is not always the case as a notice period may be worked.    The current legislation
default wi
defaultll 
defaulttherefore 
defaultgive rise to the anomalous situation that individuals may be genuine equity partners and taxed as such for many years, but that they are taxed as employees in their final year of membership.  We strongly recommend an exemption from the provisi
defaultons for anyone in their final 12 months of membership provided they have not been a salaried member in any of the previous three (say) years.
default11
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe introduction of specific rules taxing individual members on profits allocated to a non individual member of a 
defaultpartnership
default is anticipated to 
defaultcause difficulties for many mixed partnerships because the legislation
default 
defaultis 
defaultintentionally 
defaultaimed at taxing commercial 
defaultarrangements, as well as structures specifically designed for tax avoidance.  Examples of commercial arrangemen
defaultts caught by the new rules include allocations of profits to corporates for working capital purposes, investments, or deferred profit arrangements.
default12
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever, the legislation has been drafted with anti-avoidance mainly in mind, as the legislation requires th
defaulte taxpayer to consider whether it would be reasonable to conclude that the reason some or all of the excess profits have been allocated to the corporate is attributable to the relationship between the corporate and the individual member.  Then, only a just
default and reasonable 
defaultallocation of the excess profits is taxable on the individual member.
default13
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis style of drafting is appropriate for tax avoidance legislation, where a degree of flexibility is required.  However, where the legislation has a purpose of raising additional tax from commercial arrangements it is not appropriate to have such subjecti
defaultve tests.  Such subjective concepts give rise to a high level of uncertainty as to how the legislation applies to a commercial situation.  
defaultWe believe that these should be removed as they do not make good legislation.
default14
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn summary we believe that, while the a
defaultpproach taken is drafting the legislation has the potential to achi
defaulte
defaultve clarity and restrict application to the stated policy group, it does not do so as currently drafted.
defaultGuidancedefault&#xa0;
default15
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe guidance supporting the draft legislation is 56 
defaultpages
default long.  While we
default welcome the principle of HMRC issuing guidance (and acknowledge that we would have raised concerns about lack of clarity if none had been issued) we do not believe that the guidance as currently drafted performs its correct 
defaultpurpose
default.  This should be to cla
defaultrify the legislation rather than to extend it.
default  As the guidance is not regulated by Parliament there is a risk of interpretation by HMRC which is not in accordance with Parliament’s wish.
default16
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDespite its length the guidance itself does not clarify certain key 
defaultpoints.  We have submitted several additional examples and questions to HMRC in an attempt to obtain certainty on our own position and that of many of our clients.  We attach as 
defaultan 
defaultappendi
defaultx
default 
defaulta 
defaultcop
defaulty
default of
